Baabdullah et al. [52] reported that both the usability of mobile banking applications and perceived customer service significantly influence customer satisfaction. Specifically, usability was found to increase satisfaction(
β p = , &lt; 0.2556 0.05
), whereas customer service exhibited a stronger effect(
β p = , &lt; 0.5404 0.001
). Customer satisfaction was identified as a mediator in the relationships between usability and loyalty, and between customer service and loyalty, indicating that higher satisfaction leads to greater customer loyalty in mobile banking contexts. Similarly, Karjaluoto et al. [58] demonstrated significant relationships between mobile banking satisfaction and multiple antecedents, including service quality, technology acceptance, and credibility factors. These satisfaction levels were also found to influence behavioral outcomes, such as actual usage, continued intention to use, and customer loyalty.
